Today’s lecture focused on pattern printing using looping constructs in Java. Pattern programs are used to improve 
logical thinking and understanding of loop control. The mentor explained that nested for loops are mainly used for p
attern printing, where the outer loop controls the number of rows and the inner loop controls the number of columns. 

By adjusting loop limits and print statements, different shapes such as pyramids, triangles, and number patterns can be 
created.

The session emphasized understanding the flow of loops. First, the outer loop starts and represents each row. Inside it, 
the inner loop runs and prints symbols such as stars or numbers. After the inner loop finishes, the cursor moves to the 
next line using println(). This process repeats until all rows are printed. Proper control of loop variables and conditions 
is necessary to get the correct pattern shape.

The mentor also explained that pattern printing requires careful observation of how many rows and columns are needed and 
how values change in each row. This helps in developing problem-solving skills and improves programming logic. 
Nested loops are very useful in such cases because they allow repetition inside another repetition.

The working flow starts from the outer loop, which controls rows. For each row, the inner loop executes and prints 
the required output. Once the condition becomes false, the loops stop, and the pattern is completed.
